Context:
E2E tests use Playwright fixtures from `e2e/fixtures.ts` and helpers from `e2e/helpers.ts`. The standard pattern:

```typescript
import type { McpClient, McpServer } from './fixtures.js';
import { expect, test } from './fixtures.js';
import { waitForExtensionConnected, waitForLog } from './helpers.js';

const initAndListTools = async (
  mcpServer: McpServer,
  mcpClient: McpClient,
): Promise<Array<{ name: string; description: string }>> => {
  await waitForExtensionConnected(mcpServer);
  await waitForLog(mcpServer, 'plugin(s) mapped');
  return mcpClient.listTools();
};
```

See `e2e/browser-tools.e2e.ts` for the reference pattern — it imports `BROWSER_TOOL_NAMES` from helpers and checks each tool appears. For this test file, create a dedicated `test.describe('browser_notify')` block.

The `mcpClient.listTools()` returns `Array<{ name: string; description: string }>` — use this to verify the tool name and description. To check the input schema, use `mcpClient.callTool` or check the raw tool definition if available.

Fixtures needed: `mcpServer`, `extensionContext` (required for WebSocket connection), `mcpClient`.

The `BROWSER_TOOL_NAMES` array in helpers.ts is derived from `BROWSER_TOOLS_CATALOG` — after US-002 regenerates the catalog, `browser_notify` will automatically be in this array.

Constraints:
- Do NOT modify existing browser-tools.e2e.ts — create a separate file
- Use the standard fixture pattern (mcpServer, extensionContext, mcpClient)

